s of colonial studies in an effort to get beyond the tendency in the field to focus on a generic colonialism located sometime between 1492 and the 1960s and somewhere in the "West." Broad-ranging, cogently argued, and with a historical focus that moves from Africa to South Asia to Europe, these essays, most published here for the first time, propose a fuller engagement in the give-and-take of history, not least in the ways in which concepts usually attributed to Western universalism—including citizenship and equality—were defined and reconfigured by political mobilizations in colonial contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDecolonizationxHistoriography. 0aDecolonizationzAfricaxHistoriography. 0aImperialismxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aafrica.  acivic.  acolonial contexts.  acolonial studies.  acolonial theory.  acolonialism.  acolonization.  adiaspora.  aessay collection.  aeurope.  aglobalization.  ahistorians.  ahistorical perspective.  ahistory of colonialism.  ahuman condition.  ahumanities.  aimperialism.  amodernity.  anational identity.  anationalism.  anonfiction essays.  apostcolonial.  aretrospective.  asocial sciences.  asouth asia.  atextbooks.  atheoretical.  awestern scholars.  aworld history.  aworld powers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024214240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093861840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938618/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY